<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#F7F7F7"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#9FA6C4"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000000" FACE="Verdana">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Eanin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">I am a sixth lvl bard, so I am fairly new to my character.  I have read stuff about twisting and have tried it out today, but I  don't knwo if I am ding it correctly.  Can someone please explain it to me.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Mad Dawgg</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">to know if you are doing it correctly look at  the top right corner of your screen where spell indicaters show up! If you have two indicaters at one time you are twisting properly!</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Glane</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">When I twist two songs, 6 seconds between songs seems to work fairly easily.  When fighting solo I usually twist Anthem and Hymn.  For me the best way to work on twisting was when I ran.  You can focus on the Hymn and Selo. By the time you find your next enemy you are healed up.  Good Hunting.<P>Glane the Bard of Quellious<BR>Level 11</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">The Singer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">You can twist up to three songs at once. However it's not too effective with three until level 12. Start with two songs at level 6...healing and chant. Then when you get warsong use that and healing. Next when you get anthem use that warsong and healing...you lose it sometimes on a bash but three is better than two. At level 12 Use Bellow, Warsong, and anthem/healing. <BR>For groups use healing, bellow, and anthem. Now get this...sometimes you have to decide on what ya wanna do. When fighting magic i may use two of the guardian songs. Trust me they really help. And to really confuse you as to what to use..lvl 18 you get a upgraded version the second song. It lowers AC of monsters..i am not sure how much and it does damage. At 20 you get a AC lowering and attack speed lowering also. When Combining these two i have noticed a difference in the creaturs. Be careful because they have a area effect. Bah i am getting long winded! <BR>Goodbye and good luck<P>Anavara<BR>Bristlebane Server<P>P.S. I have a soft spot for young bards so if you see me wave to me and I have been known to Drop the youngins a few plat!</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">The Singer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Geez I blab</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Eanin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Thanks again for all the advice regarding twisting.  I am now a level 12 (so...so..very close to 13, and have gotten the hang of twisting.  The only thing I hate is when my computer starts to lag, and my timing of twist get all screwed up.  Should I try to stick to a group if my lag gets real bad (kind of a safety net)?<P>One more quetion.  I have a mino axe (max on skill) and a dirk (not good at all...awful).  What do you suggest that I use.  I am still trying to figure out what weapons I will be using once I get dual weild.  I know it is a long time away (4 more levels), but I like to get a head start on things.  <P><BR>Eanin-  Prexus 12th song</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Medowlark</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">When I am Twisting, instead of timing my singing, I just wait until the text area notifies me that the song is in effect. Then I start into the next song and then the next ... <P>Seems to me that I have often been close to Twisting four songs. Instead of a complete overlapping of tunes, as happens with three songs, the first song usually ends just as the fourth song has started. Essentially, this is Twisting four songs ... with just one small dropped beat. However, a skillful Bard can work it so her audience -- who is not quite as knowledgeable -- will never even notice. <P>On a side note: I once banded with a party that included two other bards besides myself. You have never heard such sweet sounds nor seen such a spectacular light show as when 3 Spellsingers are Twisting 2 or 3 songs apiece. Magnificent!<P>Just my thoughts. <P>------------------<BR>Your humble servant,<P>Medowlark of Freeport<BR>Bard of the 11th Circle<BR>>>> Prexus Server <<<<P><p>[This message has been edited by Medowlark (edited 08-16-1999).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Glane</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Are the Guardian Songs worth using?  I usually twist Bellow, Chords, and Anthem.  It seems to be a good mix in a group fighting multiple opponents.  Do the guardian songs make a noticeable difference?  Also I have found Cinda's Charismatic Carillon is a wonderful song and well worth the coin.  It will save you a lot fighting to get a good reaction out of the dwarf Bloodforge so you can give him Trumpy's head to get the Bloodforge Hammer and not to mention help get better prices from the merchants that con apprehensive.  To bad bards can’t use the Bloodforge Hammer, but it sells easily for 25pp.<P>Glane the Bard on Quellious<BR>13th Level</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">HarlequinII</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Guardian songs do have a use.  Being a Bard on Vallon Zek, well, it helps make the opposing spellcasters a lot easier to kill.  Twisting Purifying and Elemental, with drums, I can add +38 to everyones Magic Resistance.<P>Add to that a Hymn or Anthem, and the opposing party usually loses.  Quickly.<BR>Root !?  Hehn, what Root ?  Accelerado cancels is np, but it usually get resisted by my party.<P>Versus NPC casters, high level ones at that, the big resistance boost to magic helps everyone in the party.  I don't normally keep the songs mem'ed, but with swap songs when knowingly facing an enemy caster.<P>Nintarri, 20th Bard, Quellious<BR>Barraq, 13th Bard, Vallon Zek<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Balrin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">  Being a 22nd lvl bard, I find that cycling<BR>CoD(Cords of Dis.), Bellow, and DDD(Denons 18th lvl area Dot), is a great way to bring down an opponent fast, while at the same time wielding two DoT affect weapons... I also like using Warsong, Healing, and Bellow/20th lvl binding... For real damage/healing, I would say go with all Insturments and damage, I was able to bring down 4 lvl 17-21 lvl Goblins in Perma, including a Mendicant(Caster/healer gob) all with just my fists and songs... was very cool, was lvl 19 at the time...<P>Balrin Soulsinger, Bard of Bristlebane<BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
